  <exercise permid="eAe">
    <statement>
      <p permid="nyr">
        Which of the graphs below are bipartite?
        Justify your answers.
      </p>

      <sidebyside permid="huK" widths="20% 20% 20% 20%" margins="auto" valign="middle">

        <image permid="BBW">

				<latex-image>
					\begin{tikzpicture}
  \draw (-1,1) \v -- (0,2) \v -- (1,1) \v -- (0,0) \v -- (-1,1) -- (0,1) \v -- (1,1);
\end{tikzpicture}
				</latex-image>
        </image>

        <image permid="hJf">

				<latex-image>
					\begin{tikzpicture}
  \draw (0:1) \v -- (120:1) \v -- (60:1) \v -- (300:1) \v -- (180:1) \v -- (240:1) \v -- cycle;
\end{tikzpicture}
				</latex-image>
        </image>

        <image permid="NQo">

				<latex-image>
					\begin{tikzpicture}
  \draw (360/7:1) \v -- (2*360/7:1) \v -- (3*360/7:1) \v -- (4*360/7:1) \v -- (5*360/7:1) \v -- (6*360/7:1) \v -- (0:1) \v -- cycle;
\end{tikzpicture}
				</latex-image>
        </image>

        <image permid="tXx">

				<latex-image>
					\begin{tikzpicture}
  \draw (0,0) \v;
  \foreach \x in {0,...,7}
  \draw (0,0) -- (\x*360/8+22.5:1) \v;
\end{tikzpicture}
				</latex-image>
        </image>

      </sidebyside>
    </statement>
    <solution permid="bFy">
      <p permid="lJe">
        Three of the graphs are bipartite.
        The one which is not is <m>C_7</m>
        (second from the right).
        To see that the three graphs are bipartite,
        we can just give the bipartition into two sets <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>,
        as labeled below:
      </p>

			<!-- TODO: justify these answers a little better -->
      <sidebyside permid="NBT" widths="20% 23% 20%" margins="auto" valign="middle">

        <image permid="cZm">

					<latex-image>
						\begin{tikzpicture}
		\draw (-1,1) \vb{\footnotesize $A$} -- (0,2) \vb{\footnotesize $B$} -- (1,1) \vb{\footnotesize $A$} -- (0,0) \vb{\footnotesize $B$} -- (-1,1) -- (0,1) \vb{\footnotesize $B$} -- (1,1);
	\end{tikzpicture}
					</latex-image>
        </image>

        <image permid="Jgv">

					<latex-image>
						\begin{tikzpicture}
		\draw (0:1) \vr{\footnotesize $B$} -- (120:1) \vl{\footnotesize $A$} -- (60:1) \vr{\footnotesize $B$} -- (300:1) \vr{\footnotesize $A$} -- (180:1) \vl{\footnotesize $B$} -- (240:1) \vl{\footnotesize $A$} -- cycle;
	\end{tikzpicture}
					</latex-image>
        </image>

        <image permid="pnE">

					<latex-image>
						\begin{tikzpicture}
		\draw (0,0) \va{\footnotesize $B$};
		\foreach \x in {0,...,7}
		\draw (0,0) -- (\x*360/8+22.5:1) \va{\footnotesize $A$};
	\end{tikzpicture}
					</latex-image>
        </image>

      </sidebyside>

      <p permid="RQn">
        The graph <m>C_7</m> is not bipartite because it is an <em>odd</em> cycle.
        You would want to put every other vertex into the set <m>A</m>,
        but if you travel clockwise in this fashion,
        the last vertex will also be put into the set <m>A</m>,
        leaving two <m>A</m> vertices adjacent
        (which makes it not a bipartition).
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise permid="KHn">
    <statement>
      <p permid="TFA">
        For which <m>n \ge 3</m> is the graph <m>C_n</m> bipartite?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution permid="HMH">
      <p permid="xXw">
        <m>C_n</m> is bipartite if and only if <m>n</m> or is even.
        Put every other vertex into the first part,
        the others into the second.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise permid="qOw">
    <statement>
      <p permid="zMJ">
        For each of the following,
        try to give two <em>different</em>
        unlabeled graphs with the given properties,
        or explain why doing so is impossible.

        <ol permid="YKS">
          <li permid="xnC">
            <p permid="Qba">
              Two different trees with the same number of vertices and the same number of edges.
              A tree is a connected graph with no cycles.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li permid="duL">
            <p permid="wij">
              Two different graphs with 8 vertices all of degree 2.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li permid="JBU">
            <p permid="cps">
              Two different graphs with 5 vertices all of degree 4.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li permid="pJd">
            <p permid="IwB">
              Two different graphs with 5 vertices all of degree 3.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution permid="nTQ">
      <p permid="eeF">
        <ol permid="gpr">
          <li permid="VQm">
            <p permid="oDK">
              For example:
            </p>

            <sidebyside permid="tJc" widths="20% 20%" margins="auto" valign="bottom">

              <image permid="EwC">

								<latex-image>
									\begin{tikzpicture}
									\draw (0,0) \v -- (-1,1) \v (0,0) -- (0,1) \v (0,0) -- (1,1) \v;
									\end{tikzpicture}
								</latex-image>
              </image>

              <image permid="kDL">

								<latex-image>
									\begin{tikzpicture}
									\draw (0,0) \v -- (-1,1) \v (0,0) -- (.5,.5) \v -- (1,1) \v;
									\end{tikzpicture}
								</latex-image>
              </image>

            </sidebyside>

          </li>

          <li permid="BXv">
            <p permid="UKT">
              This is not possible if we require the graphs to be connected.
              If not, we could take <m>C_8</m> as one graph and two copies of <m>C_4</m> as the other.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li permid="ieE">
            <p permid="ASc">
              Not possible.
              If you have a graph with 5 vertices all of degree 4, then every vertex must be adjacent to every other vertex.
              This is the graph <m>K_5</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li permid="OlN">
            <p permid="gZl">
              This is not possible.
              In fact, there is not even one graph with this property
              (such a graph would have <m>5\cdot 3/2 = 7.5</m> edges).
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise permid="WVF">
    <statement>
      <p permid="fTS">
        Let <m>k_1, k_2, \ldots,
        k_j</m> be a list of numbers that sum to <m>n</m> (i.e, <m>\sum_{i=1}^j k_i = n</m>).
        Use two graphs containing <m>n</m> vertices to explain why
        <me permid="Mbb">
          \sum_{i = 1}^j \binom{k_i}{2} \le \binom{n}{2}
        </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <hint permid="Aii">
      <p permid="qsX">
        One of the graphs will not be connected, unless <m>j=1</m>.
      </p>
    </hint>
    <solution permid="UaZ">
      <p permid="KlO">
        First consider the graph <m>K_n</m>,
        which has <m>\binom{n}{2}</m> vertices.
        Compare this to a graph with <m>n</m> vertices consisting of <m>j</m> components,
        disconnected from each other,
        each a complete graph on its vertices.
        In fact, the first component will be <m>K_{k_1}</m>,
        the second <m>K_{k_2}</m>, and so on.
        The total number of edges in this graph will be <m>\sum_{i=1}^j\binom{k_j}{2}</m>.
        Of course this disconnected graph will have fewer edges than <m>K_n</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

